         <ref id="ref1">
            <label>1</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Probably the best-known example of a debate of this sort is that concerning the conflicting interpretations of<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Henry James</string-name>
               </person-group>'s novella<source>
                  <italic>The Turn of the Screw</italic>
               </source>(see<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Rimmon-Kenan</string-name>
               </person-group>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref2">
            <label>2</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">In principle, every fictional narrator may be considered a deceiver of his audience, or, as I will call him, an “other-deceiver,” whether because he narrates events that never happened (in part or not at all) and presents them as the whole truth, or due to the Platonic conception according to which truth in fiction is an imitation or a pale reflection of a truer reality of a higher order. But I have no intention of discussing fictional truth in its referential meaning, that is, with regard to its correspondence to the external world. I accept Felíx Martínez-Bonati's view that readers must have a basic trust in the narrator's words, as long as they consider the story fictional. This leads to the conclusion that a violation of the literary convention of basic trust between the narrator and readers must be based on textual signs indicating a deviation from the norm of reliability. In writing this, I do not mean to state that the<italic>same</italic>textual signs would necessarily be understood by all readers as evidence of the narrator's unreliability; a certain sign may be interpreted by one reader, guided by a certain theory or belief, as an expression of unreliability, whereas another reader may interpret the same sign otherwise. I will use the term<italic>narrating character</italic>since my discussion concerns narrators who are also characters in the stories they tell. I further believe that all kinds of unreliable narrators are personified, even though they are not necessarily homodiegetic (see also<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Zerweck</string-name>
               </person-group>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref3">
            <label>3</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">See<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>David Packman</string-name>
               </person-group>, who argues that Humbert reads Dolores's body as a text.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref4">
            <label>4</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">About the synecdoche as Humbert's favorite linguistic figure, see<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Nomi Tamir-Ghez</string-name>
               </person-group>(<fpage>172</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref5">
            <label>5</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">The term<italic>naturalization</italic>is frequently used in this context, for example by Kathleen Wall.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref6">
            <label>6</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">It may be argued that Humbert's “real” name is not real either, since it is a name in a fictive world, but in that world—that is, from the point of view of the narrating character and of the reader who basically trusts the narrator—such a distinction is meaningful. See also<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Yacobi</string-name>
               </person-group>.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref7">
            <label>7</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">The impression of unreliability that the narrating character evokes in the readers caused different critics (for example, Pifer; Stegner; and Toker) to offer interpretations whose main significance, in my view, is that they indicate the dissolution of the text in the case of such a blatant violation of the trust contract with the reader.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref8">
            <label>8</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">I do not believe that one should identify the novel's<italic>fictional</italic>reader with its<italic>implied</italic>reader (see<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Iser</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <fpage>33</fpage>). It is more accurate to consider the former an internal narratee, similar to the jury.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref9">
            <label>9</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Since my discussion centers on the interaction between the narrating character and his (internal and external) narratees, I focus on one kind of effect created by the inconsistency—the<italic>psychological</italic>effect, treated by Rampton. Frosch, and Stegner point to two additional effects that are the consequence of inconsistency: the<italic>artistic</italic>effect and the<italic>judicial</italic>effect.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
